segments.text: I was raised in the house with him, Mr. Felix McMillan.
And they taught me mighty good.
They teach me good.
They said, I remember, says, Joe, I said, yes, sir.
When we are dead and in heaven, they said, we want to raise you as an intelligent nigger.
We want you to have good friends like we've got.
Say you'll never be scratched by good, rich, sensible white folks because they can tell who you are by your raising and your compliments.
To show that you've been raised, he said, not by the color, but by the white.
I washed in iron.
Some days I'd wash a hundred pieces.
Some, every morning, I'd have five beds to mix up, five fires to mix, and the children to dress, and churning to do.
And after that, but then I'd have some parts of the day.
But I had all that to do every day.
Raised right up in the house.
You know, I remember telling them one story.
You know, I slept like in this room, and they slept joining the rooms to me, you know.
They said, Joe, if it gets cold, come in our room.
I said, great, great, great.
Well, can't you tell a story about your open girlhood days and about who raised you?
Go ahead.
Come on, Jim.
No, you.
Yeah, you.
Oh, I always was a good girl.
I don't know any stories on me.
Well, did you work in the field or work in the house?
I worked in the field and the house, too.
Both places.
But I'd like to see you in the building.
Uh-huh.
Why did you like the field the best?
Well, just because I catch more good breeze and more good fresh air out in the field than I do in the kitchen, in the house.
Now, you know that.
I didn't go to the field until I was 19 years old.
I love the field.
I went to the field when I was 19 years old, and I remember the old boy said, well, Joe, you know, I had three Jims there.
And I had one Jim, two Jim Max, and one Jim Turner, Kenneth.
And, uh,
My brother Jim Mack, he was a colorful and a white Jim, you know.
He went with my old boys to look for the Jim Kennards, you know, and to put me to flying, you know.
The girl said, sir, I want you to go up there in a while to be able to sleep.
The flyer said, when Miss Dora call, you go back to the house and see to the baby stuff.
Baby went to sleep, and I slept two or three hours, and I fly to the old boy's side back.
But I didn't like the field.
Didn't go to the field.
I didn't go to the field.
What kind of work did you like best in the field?
Picking cotton.
Picking cotton.
Picking cotton.
How much could you pick in a day?
Well, 150, 60 cents.
He wasn't pickin' very hard.
Now, in them days, Miss Dora had a horse named John.
And said, Joey, you can fly, old John.
I said, yes, I know I can.
What have you got to do?
Go down in the field and fly, old John, and nothing to do.
I said, oh, I want to go to the field.
He looked at me and laughed.
You know what I tell the story.
You know what I love to do?
To hide to be in the field.
He said, well, you go out there and check the old John.
Go down there and fly with Miss Dora's cat.
And you know, I went, called old John Hiddens to the tennis ground, went down there and started dancing, and come down there sitting down by a big old old, big old neck on the street.
I was sitting down there at the beach, and he said, Joe, I said, sir, did you climb in this door at that time?
I said, yes, yes, yes.
He said, check out old John Gordy, I'll see you in a minute.
I don't know, I don't know.
I don't know, I don't know.
I don't know, I don't know.
I don't know.
Yeah.
Okay.
Well, Mr. Johnson, we're going to start off.
All right.
All right.
I want you to tell me how you got your name.
I got my name from President Jeff Davis.
The president of the Southern Confederacy.
He owned my grandfather and my father.
He brought them from Richmond, Virginia.
My grandfather was a blacksmith.
My father was a young kid, wasn't grown.
And my father had learned how to write a little bit in Richmond, Virginia before he brought me down here.
Grandfather used to keep chalk in his shop to mark the odd things.
And my father would take a piece and put it in his pocket
And passing from Master Jeff's house, he's right on the sidewalk.
And so one morning, Master Jeff come by and saw I was right on the walk.
He go up against the cook, who there, Mere Liza.
He's right on the sidewalk.
Who's right out there?
He said, I don't know, Master Jeff.
He said, come out there, I'll show you how to do it.
So he read it.
He said, Mere Liza, if you can find where I might walk out there, I can't lie to you, so he's pretty dressed.
He said, yes, Master Jeff.
So one morning, he's out for some fish water.
And she came out of this pen and she looked around and saw my father down with me right on the sidewalk.
She told him, I'll tell you.
I'll tell you something for the boy to come to the shop, come to the house, and ask him who in my life.
He said, I'll tell you if I never had a life in this machine, never had a life in my life.
So he brought me down here.
He did, yes.
He gave me a punch.
He said, I got it, my name.
My father named my idea.
He called it Mike.
That's my name.
He wrote Jeff Davis' name.
He wrote two names.
They were dirty.
They were a rich boy.
They were a rich boy.
He said, uh-huh, Ike, that's pretty nice of you.
They sent him back to the shop, and Martha Giles started to listen to me, and he got two teachers.
He opened a nice school.
He educated all these niggas.
He made my father a souvenir.
And he made a couple of nice little gummies as bookkeepers.
And all in all, they made different things.
Farms, cotton, sawmills, gins, and all that kind of stuff.
That's the record of my father and Colonel Montgomery.
Colonel was born in those events.
He was born on Hurricane Plantation, just a giant piece of biofield.
I was born on biofield.
Moshe Jeff had fire plantations over there.
Hurricane, biofield, hurricane, power mine, and lake place.
It all belonged to Moshe Jeff.
And he had all those niggas from different places, all the plans to come back to school.
Night school.
He gave them all a form of education.
When they all got free, they could take it themselves.
He had so much business, he couldn't hire people who got business.
He had kids.
He needed education so he could tend to his business.
He wanted to learn to tend to Moshe's business.
He was admired.
Obedient.
Kept while he was gone, he obeyed Moshe.
Once Moshe was going to land in the boogie, in the hack,
The gate was locked.
The same old man I tell you about, old man Jack Rayner, he got to the gate, he said, Marcy, this gate's locked.
He said, well, Jack, it's locked.
It's my gate.
Bring it down.
It's my gate.
So the boy picked it up, and Jack didn't break down the gate.
He took the fence down and drove on through there, and the wagon went on behind him, you understand, with the bands, cams, and land.
And when he come back, they put the fence up.
That's the original Marcy up in his nickels.
And when he met a Negro on the road, first thing he must have done was look at the ceiling and say, it's that time.
And everyone would give him the same thing back.
Give him honor.
And when he'd come home from New Orleans up to the bend, Steve would land.
He'd unload the freight and load the cotton.
And he'd get the bait there and sleep.
And the captain would say, is Mr. Davis up?
No, he ain't up.
I really want him up.
Wait till he wake up.
Mr. Davis wake up.
And he'd come downstairs, he'd pick up a chair and all, pack it up out on the land, send it down to his hack, and he'd get up and buy it about the third time before he'd get in his hack.
He never allowed him to do anything like that.
He just obeyed him.
They all obeyed Marshal Jeff.
The white people would always go out to the bank fishing and hunting on the banks when Marshal Jeff would be in the base fleet.
They never did anything like that.
They always obeyed him all the time, white and black.
He gave them all.
His best man would escort him home, escort him back when he got ready.
And, uh, he's on a pageant that one day on Lake Place.
He told Mr. Corleone, he said, Mr. Corleone, I'm going home tomorrow.
He said, don't get to feed my niggas.
And he gets to lay them by the crops.
Let them be with them, cut the cordwood.
But don't disturb them.
I want them undisturbed.
He said, anything happen to any of my niggas, you wait and see Mr. Davis.
And don't forget I'm Mr. Davis.
He said, my nigga is my summer shade.
He's my weather fire.
He's my umbrella.
Don't disturb him.
So they laid by a crop over there with sweeps.
Mr. Colt, I want you to lay a crop with color fields.
That wouldn't do no good.
It wouldn't cut those vines.
The Negro who must have been educated, one who actually laid by a crop with double sweeps.
And he come back and helped Colt.
And the next day he fired away, man.
He wanted to play and live like he wanted to.
He laid by the crop like he wanted, you understand.
He had his crop cleaned, Master Jeff, cut them with those big switches and go in the middle, clean them out, you understand, which he couldn't do.
He kept those vines, jumped those vines.
The trees killed all of them.
He cleaned his place out, the lake place.
He had a hundred trees over there.
He had all those mules from different plants, you understand, from where he cleaned that place.
He had plenty of stock, you know.
These are real stock.
All you stick now on Hurricane, there's a pass over there, old Long Hill Sugar, outside the roadside, you know.
All that stock he bought from Master Jeff, all that stock.
Mules, cows, horses, everything else.
Horses, everything else.
Sheep, goats, all brought to him.
Now he had those sheep sheared, seven times a year, and they had wool and shipped it somewhere.
Say you do cotton, gather the gin and pack it.
He had three, four steam gins, understand, see?
These steam gins on Hurricane, one on Briarfield, one on everything else.
Three gins, I know.
He had three gins, three gins.
And whatever he wanted, he got slaughtered on Hurricane for a steam milk quarter.
And when you want a thing done, you just put it on paper and it's gone.
It's done.
You tell me how the story as to how Isaac T. Montgomery's father saved the plantation during the Civil War for him?
Yeah, well, when the young was coming south to look after those places down there, he robbed somebody.
I'm being serious.
And Ben went to Ole Miss, Miss Irene, his wife.
She said, Ole Miss, I've got to go to Richmond.
I've got to see Mars Jeff.
She said, you want to see Mars Jeff with Ben?
I said, I've got to see him.
She said, no, Miss, you can't do no good.
I can't.
I don't want to see you.
I want to see Mars Jeff.
I want a passport.
Send me to Richmond to see Mars Jeff.
So they gave him Ben the passport.
And I went to Richmond.
He got some bread in the sack.
I went to Richmond to see him.
I went to Richmond to see him.
I went to Richmond to see him.
I went to Richmond to see him.
I went to Richmond to see him.
I went to Richmond to see him.
I went to Richmond to see him.
I went to Richmond to see him.
I went to Richmond to see him.
Walk in there, howdy, Marshal Jeff.
Hey, Ben's been here.
Can I come in and see you, Marshal Jeff?
He said, Ben, I'm telling you all you know.
Howdy, everybody at home.
He said, everybody's welcome, Marshal Jeff, but somebody come and see you about.
He said, where is Ben?
He said, Marshal Jeff, those Yankees are coming south, near Bixbury.
They're coming down south, getting all that folks land, and robbing the niggers, stealing all the mules, and they're in pursuit of David's land.
That's what I want you to do.
He said, where is Ben?
I want you to leave the land to me.
Five.
He said, then I'm going to go, girl.
I said, don't you belong to me.
The land's mine.
You're mine.
I said, how you know?
I said, my God, free me, man.
I said, bring you right.
So he took him big up to the San Diego coast.
And leave the land to him and free him.
And made notes, some notes unpaid, you understand.
And three or four unpaid.
And so I'm back home, and the angels got out into the bin out home there.
The angels come, you understand, and they ask the days of the land, the days of the farm.
The days ain't got no land.
The old man is here.
He's gone to Ben Montgomery.
Why is Ben Montgomery here?
He said, come here, Ben.
This old man, he asked, where'd you get that?
Brought it from my old master.
He called Mrs.
He asked her to bring his old papers, you understand.
Show it to him.
He made those notes and papers, you understand.
Uh-huh.
That is your land.
I don't know what kind of nigger your land.
But I don't.
I don't cross the river.
It's my land, though.
And when the freedom time come back, Master Jeff come on home, you understand, and he give him a cotton basket of money.
What he done?
Cotton basket, cotton basket.
Oh, not quite high as the table.
Like that old basket now.
That was on Bradfield Place, on Bradfield, right in Master Jeff's house.
Well, this band, you say that Jefferson Davis organized for his slaves.
Yes, sir.
Can you tell me a little something about that band?
Tell me a little something about that band.
You started to tell me about this band that...
Jefferson Davis organized for his slaves.
Yes, he organized that band for his Negroes.
And Davis had been on barkeep transition.
And he hired a man named Charles Morgan to teach them boys music.
And he taught those boys music.
They got to where he could play.
They escorted him from Lennon up home in a wagon.
And his band would play for him going and coming.
And after he got through, he played in a bomber's uniform.
And in that band, there's been bands.
That's quite everywhere he went.
How many pieces were in the band?
Fourteen.
Fourteen men in the band.
Fourteen men.
What kind of music did they play?
Do you remember any of the pieces they played?
Oh, Lord, yes, indeed.
No, I played myself.
I played Grand National, Fourth Watch, East Richmond, Mount Rose, Dream On,
Flea the Buried to the Mountain, Nut Gilded, Dance Theater, Armistice Surgeon, Fire on Quickstep, all that kind of stuff.
We play it up here in the store.
Oh, a name, Samoy, if you remember any of them.
That's Pete Dreamall.
That's Pete Dreamall.
Did you ever play this piece, Dixie, that was so popular?
Dixie, oh yeah, Pete Dixie.
Yeah, I ain't paid enough.
And, uh... Flora Fluck.
Flora Fluck.
And...
I don't know the other people.
I'm a soldier, I think it was.
And, uh...
Well, did you, uh, you all didn't play any plantation songs?
No, sir.
I played street music myself.
I got music.
I didn't risk having pebbles.
And Lion Healer.
And George Sullivan.
That's where I got music.
We got a band from Lion Healer in Chicago.
Well, did the other slaves on the plantation sing any of the plantation songs?
They sing in the fields and sing around the place?
Did you ever sing in the yard?
for him when he had visitors, anything like that?
Well, the kids would sing some little funny things, you know, around there, and dance and all that got, you know.
They had a little play, used to play down there, play, uh, scripture sound, you understand?
Dance to the bottle.
Sit down all day, you know, and they'd dance, you know, of course, scripture sound.
Everybody danced scripture sound, they'd ring play, you know.
And, uh, they'd go dance, each time, dance with that bottle, he'd dance with the bottle, and the whole bottle would break.
set up, you understand, and just play that song around that place and sing Scoop to Sam and dance with that brother, or that Rick.
Well, do you remember any of the words of Scoop to Sam?
No, I don't remember those words now.
Which I could relate to.
It's a long... And I heard we had a little song you sang, too, going to the lady, yes, I am, and she was talking to the man.
Do you know that?
No, that's the first word I think about, thank you.
Do you remember any of the other lines of it?
No, sir.
No, sir.
Well, did you all have any dancers at that time, or had you joined the church?
Yeah, we had dancers.
We had dancers.
We had dancers, you know, this, this, this, quite a quantity.
We had dancers, 32 on the set, and 24 on the set.
They had this thing called Tommy's Apartment, and dancing apartment I got in, Tommy's Swing.
All that kind of stuff, you understand, see?
And, uh, he probably went to the bar.
He had a bar, you know, where they bought candy and so on, I guess, you know.
And apples and oranges, you understand, he'd carry a pot and spin a dime or a quarter on it and buy him candy.
I'll cook something, I guess, you know.
You know, he had no silverware, you understand.
He had, uh, lemonade made in the barrel.
He had no, nothing like silverware then.
No more silverware.
Did you all sing any songs at those dances while you were doing the quadrille and the promenade?
No, I didn't sing.
I had to think about dancing and hooping hollies.
Did you have anybody to call figures?
Oh, yes, indeed.
I had a fellow here.
He played my band's call figures.
A fellow named Hicks Singleton.
He did now.
He was naturally a smart fellow.
He was about my age.
He was a jolly fellow.
He knew all that kind of stuff, that dancing stuff, you know.
I never was a dancer.
I played myself in music.
I liked music.
Did you play for these dancers?
Oh, yes, yeah.
Yes, sir.
Well, what year did you leave the...
and leave Davis' band?
Davis' band left Davis' band in the year of 84.
Now Davis' band came out here from Fiskeburg.
And we come to Fiskeburg and stayed there till the 87.
And come out here and get in touch with Mason McGinnis, his father-in-law, who was one of the supervisors of the old company.
He was a white man at the time, see.
And give him this part of this land where he could dig out up here and make it to the new city with his Negroes.
And they got him caught up here and dug this land.
And I came with me and another boy named Sheldon Allen.
his father, his third father, my father, Peter Montgomery.
He had 12 countries, you understand.
And he lost his land, you understand, up to December.
In January, he moved a few times here.
His mother was the first one to cook bread here.
Cooked bread here in 87, on a stump.
Cooked bread on a stump.
And now he had bread.
Now he had bread.
In July 12, he even came up
big break up here, got a train at Marigold.
Walked up here, you understand?
And the men had made some stairs, course tires.
They took the sliders, picked them up, and made a shack.
And that easy man should cook that bread on the stump.
That's the push of the shack.
Right out of the stump, he made a big fire.
We made a big fire for it and put both coals, put it on the stump, and put the skillet on there, you understand?
Put the lid on the skillet and put the coal on top of the lid and make that bread.
That way you got the first bread.
That's the 87th.
How many years has it been?
Fifty-four years.
Fifty-four years.
That's right.
That's right.
I pulled a chain from this country for five years.
That line is out there.
Run that line there.
Run your 36-mile league.
I pulled that chain in 88.
And on that side, on the real road there, I pulled that line in 87.
Went to San Paolo, Costa Rica.
I'll tell you, it was about six miles away.
Now, that line, Major Fontaine, the chief engineer, told Montgomery that this line was run by the guns of this, a hundred years ago.
He said, you'll find different designs and different trees along this line.
You can be cutting fine old lines, fine old stumps.
We go in the tree, and I found a gun by the tree, granted with some axes, and found a bottle in the tree, and all people wanted to eat that bottle.
And they couldn't get all that paper and put it on this book, you understand?
Very well, it wouldn't be because I cut the tree, you understand, see?
And they put another chip back in that tree.
That tree just cut out here, you fool there.
Yes, sir.
Now, that line runs from a land to a city group.
Doesn't stop.
Every county has its state.
It has its own supply.
It has its own supply.
That line down there runs all this land from here to Shelby to your white land.
From here to Marygrove to your white land.
Cutting the canes, surveying, I had no team on that.
Just, just being a little bit by.
Full team cutting out there.
Major Thornton.
Major Thornton was the chief in there.
Well, how many families were here the next year?
Next year?
Oh, we got, we had about 15 families the next year.
Just about 15 families.
Next year, we had about 15 families come here.
About, that's been now the next year.
Becoming advertised, you understand, getting people to come here.
They come from the old country, the South, you understand, see?
Kootenai, they had them come by letter and by advertising paper.
Newspaper, you understand?
They had the paper out there.
After the trip that I got, you know, he's trying to tell me all around the country.
They all come here on account of Kootenai.
They know what he's trying to do.
Tell all the folks in the land.
Come to Daisy Bend, where we left Daisy Bend.
They all come to the bend.
They come across the road to Newtown, out of the Asian Hills, from Peaksburg.
Come back to Kootenai because they know what he's trying to do.
Give them all a home.
And they bought that land, and it's gone now.
The land here is supposed to be gone.
Yes, sir.
Well, when would you say that you had your greatest prosperity here?
Greatest prosperity?
In life we had here when Cousin I.S.U.
lived, and Charles Banks, and John Francis.
It was the life of Mount Byrd.
And since they're gone, why is Mount Byrd gone?
There's no backbone.
There's no backbone in this curriculum here at all.
You need somebody to get in front.
Every gang has to have a leader.
If a gang of chickens can't have a leader, well, they got no leader, you understand.
So you need leadership.
That's what they ain't got.
Well, did you form a band when you came here to Mount Byard?
Yes, sir.
We were two bands here.
Two brass bands.
Yes, sir.
And the first teacher of that band we had, a fellow from my home, told him to send his band down home there.
He's a young fella.
Named Wilster.
He played in a band down there when I was quite big, I played in a band.
About to go with the band, you understand.
And he, when he come up there, you understand, he said, let's get up in the band.
I said, all right.
And we saved a little money, and we started the line here in Chicago, and bought a band on, part on Crave, $750.
And give it a chance to pay for it, you understand, see.
And we bought that band and started playing, started learning how to play good music.
I kind of knew really, and he knew already,
And matter of fact, yes, London had a good band.
They had a band of 14 boys.
And the other boys were working in stands and ties like that.
I was pulling the chains through the swamps, surveying, recognizing, but never getting music.
And after that band were out, the place was long, I come to run a saloon there.
Well, see, that old man's been green.
Next man I had in London, I had that band practicing there in a saloon.
I was running a saloon for 50.
I took a young band in there, you understand.
That band came here a few years ago.
That band's all gone now.
Well, what sort of pieces were you playing about 1890?
Do you remember?
Oh, I played the same piece we played down yonder.
I learned the very same music.
Very same music.
10th and 12th grade music.
I learned it.
I had a piece that a white band gave me in Cleveland.
They couldn't play it.
And they gave it to me.
And I come up here and took my band and played it.
And came out and played it to them.
Yes.
Played it to them.
I know it was a man's name.
A man gave it to me.
His name was Scott Johnson.
He was snagged on Peter, but he was a man of the band.
He said, George, we can't play, but give it to y'all.
And he gave it to me.
But if he had played that week, the next week he had to go clean with some other and play with them down there.
Man, I want to hear a quick march.
I want to hear it.
I want to hear a quick march.
I never care.
It's a heartbeat minute.
I want to hear a quick march.
Yeah, an eavescake walk is the hardest thing I ever played in my life.
What is that?
An eavescake walk.
Eavescake walk?
Yes, the hardest thing I ever played in my life.
Felt great stuff.
Yes, sir.
I can't do anything but tonguing and fingering.
Yes, sir.
It's all practice solo, every bit of solo.
I never played a sight on my life.
I played a tuba and a cornet.
I can play them now.
I don't count my teeth.
One bit, two bits.
Yes, sir.
Do you have, uh, did you all have a dance hall here at Mount Bio?
Used to, yes, sir.
We had a dance hall.
A nice dance hall.
We had a dance hall in the low stairs.
I'm trying to lie down, sit down there a piece.
I found I got wet down by a train one day.
Couldn't leave it.
Wind was spots on, on the chin on top of the roof, dry.
And such a fire, couldn't put out.
Just managed to get some other tools out of that lodge, and that's all we done.
Well, what do you think of a town like this?
Do you think that because people can run a town like this?
They can, but they ain't here now.
They ain't here now.
You can't get a cross-dye if you ain't got timber.
You've got to have timber to get the cross-dye.
You can't get a bull that's seen like this that's got timber to make it out of.
If the timber's rotten, dirty, a worm-bitten wormhole there, hit him with a door.
You take a bull with a full wormhole, he's going to go on the ice at least.
Seriously, in this country.
With a wormhole.
At least.
That's perfect talk.
Sir, you've got to have hard timber.
You can't think to go out the door with a shoe on your foot and a hole in the bottom.
You've got to get your foot wet.
Well, how long have you been a member of the church?
